l meanings of victims’ bodies and confronting them with the values of audiences, religious and popular institutional settings and practices of punishment. It encompasses both the victim’s presence as an image or performed event of pain and the conundrum of the look – the transmitted ‘pain’ experienced by the watching audience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature, Moderny17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPain in literature. 0aPain in the performing arts. 0aPerforming artsxHistoryy17th century. 0aPerforming artsxHistoryy18th century. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aDutch stock trade.  aFrench tragedy.  aIrish Rebellion.  aPalermo's executions.  acolonial massacres.  adramatic cruelty.  aearly modern colonial body.  aepicurean tastes.  afemale gaze.  ahurt(ful) body.  ainfanticide.  amasochism.  apainful excitements.  areligious massacres.  asuffering.  atheatrical torture.  awounding realities.1 aBiet, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBussels, Stijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Bella, Maria Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaven, Cornelis van der, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKorsten, Frans-Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwiatkowski, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeemans, Inger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacsotay, Tomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacsotay, Tomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoscoso, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https:/